## 🔧 Production DB Incident — Root Cause & Resolution

### Root Cause

The `orders` table (500M rows, 24/7 high-frequency writes) had **only a primary key index on `id`**. Every query filtering by `user_id`, `order_date`, or `status` was performing a **full sequential scan** across 500 million rows — explaining the 10+ second response times and millions of slow query incidents daily.

### What Was Done

All three missing indexes were created using `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`, which:
- Acquires only a `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking)
- Allows INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE to continue uninterrupted throughout the build
- Was **never wrapped in a transaction block** (as required)

| Index | Column | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | User order lookups |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | Date-range queries |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | Order status filtering |

### Safety Verification

- ✅ No `AccessExclusiveLock` acquired at any point
- ✅ Zero lock conflicts detected before, during, or after
- ✅ All writes continued uninterrupted during index builds
- ✅ All three indexes confirmed present in `pg_indexes`

### Expected Impact

Queries filtering on `user_id`, `order_date`, or `status` will now use B-tree index scans instead of sequential scans — dropping response times from 10+ seconds to milliseconds for typical workloads.
